  <TEXT> 
	 <BODY> 
		<DIV1 TYPE="letter"><PB N="[1]"> 
		  <OPENER> 
			 <ADDRESS> 
				<ADDRLINE> 
				  <NAME TYPE="place">Blakely</NAME> 
				  <DATE VALUE="1821-05-06">May 6th 1821</DATE></ADDRLINE> 
			 </ADDRESS> 
			 <SALUTE>Dear 
				<NAME TYPE="person">Earl</NAME></SALUTE></OPENER> 
		  <P> I avail myself of this, the first opportunity of conveying a letter
			 to you; &mdash; We arrived at this place on the 
			 <DATE VALUE="0000-00-29">29th</DATE> &mdash;
			 <UNCLEAR>ultimo</UNCLEAR> &mdash;; after a quiet and pleasant passage from
			 <ORIG REG="New Orleans"> 
			 <NAME TYPE="place">New &mdash; Orleans</NAME></ORIG>, The ladies
			 <ADD PLACE="supralinear">only</ADD> accepting the little sickness, which
			 <HI>old ocean</HI> always tributes, as a passport through his dominions
			 &mdash;</P> 
		  <P>The 
			 <ABBR EXPAN="General">Genl</ABBR> is in waiting for information from 
			 <NAME TYPE="person"><ABBR EXPAN="Colonel">Col</ABBR> Forbes</NAME>,
			 who was appointed by the President, Agent and Commissary to carry the royal
			 order to 
			 <NAME TYPE="place">Cuba</NAME> for the surrender of the 
			 <NAME TYPE="place">Florida's</NAME> : whether he has reached 
			 <NAME TYPE="place">Pensacola</NAME>, or not, we are as yet
			 uninformed. 
			 <NAME TYPE="person">Bronough</NAME> and 
			 <NAME TYPE="person">Breckenridge</NAME> have been sent to Pensacola,
			 with a view of Reporting to the Governor of Pensacola, and ascertaining how far
			 things are in progress towards the ceremonies of exchange, we expect their
			 return <ORIG REG="today">to day</ORIG>. Our movements depend entirely upon
			 their report, or at least so much of it, as regards the <ORIG
			 REG="preparatory">perparatory</ORIG> state of the Spanish authority to carry
			 the treaty into effect &mdash; no delay will take place as the part of our
			 Government. The 
			 <ABBR EXPAN="General">Genl</ABBR> is always prepared, and will be
			 prompt and quick. The <ORIG REG="Regiment">Regimant</ORIG> at 
			 <NAME TYPE="place">Montpelier</NAME>, and the company of Artillery at
			 
			 <NAME TYPE="place">Mobile</NAME> will <ORIG REG="constitute">con
			 <PB N="[2]"> stitute</ORIG> his military force, and <UNCLEAR>in</UNCLEAR> held
			 in readiness to march when ordered; We will proceed, <ORIG
			 REG="probably">brobably</ORIG>, tomorrow for <ORIG
			 REG="Montpelier">MontPelier</ORIG>, <ORIG REG="Whenever">Whener</ORIG> we will
			 march to Pensacola.</P> 
		  <P>We are extremely anxious to leave this place, notwithstanding the
			 efforts of the citizens to make us as comfortable as possible &mdash; they have
			 served us with, dinners, suppers, <HI>sermons</HI> and all that such of
			 <ADD PLACE="supralinear">thing called</ADD> civility, which a sickly town a bad
			 market and a poor country can hardly make agreeable, and can at most but prove
			 the good wishes of the people &mdash; <UNCLEAR> 
			 <NAME TYPE="person">Call</NAME></UNCLEAR> arrived here on the 
			 <DATE VALUE="0000-00-01">1st</DATE> 
			 <ABBR EXPAN="instant">inst.</ABBR> in good health. He brings no news
			 from 
			 <NAME TYPE="place">Tennessee</NAME> later than what you have &mdash;
			 All friends were well : 
			 <NAME TYPE="person"><ABBR EXPAN="Colonel">Col.</ABBR> Butler</NAME>
			 is a provisional Commissioner to take possession of 
			 <NAME TYPE="place"><ABBR EXPAN="Saint">St</ABBR> Augustine</NAME>,
			 and is on his way to that place. This provision in the 
			 <ABBR EXPAN="Colonels">Colns</ABBR> commission, arrives from 
			 <NAME TYPE="person"> 
				<ABBR EXPAN="General">Genl</ABBR> Gaines</NAME> being ordered to 
			 <NAME TYPE="place">Washington</NAME> whom you know was the first
			 appointed to execute that business &mdash;</P> 
		  <P>The people, I understand, are running from all parts of our country
			 to Pensacola, like Sandhill cranes from snow storms; I am afraid our western
			 boys will miss their aim, and will soon back again with hard times to their
			 brush heaps, for of all countries I have ever seen, I think this promises
			 least, to that <PB N="[3]"> plain sailing, forming character which attaches to
			 our Western countrymen generally. Pensacola if healthy, may attain some
			 eminence in a commercial point of view &mdash; The character which our nation
			 may give it, the safety of its Port, and the certainty of its market may induce
			 <ORIG REG="capitalism">capotalism</ORIG> to remove there; but this granted, and
			 all the fashionable report which is promised it, I think its greatness much
			 overrated, and this trumpeting <HI>mania</HI> of many of our people, will and
			 in <HI>feverish hard times.</HI> This is no business of ours, I shall therefore
			 say no more on the subject.</P> 
		  <P>I am sorry that I was compelled to leave 
			 <NAME TYPE="place"><ORIG REG="New Orleans">New &mdash;
				Orleans</ORIG></NAME>, before you had finished my portrait. I will
			 <GAP REASON="document damaged"> you again shortly, and will tell you then,
			 whether I will have an opportunity of seeing you again soon. if I shall not see
			 you and <ADD PLACE="supralinear">you</ADD> can make a
			 <UNCLEAR>tolerable</UNCLEAR> likeness without farther sitting, I shall thank
			 you to do so, and present it to my mother, 
			 <NAME TYPE="person">Mr Sanders</NAME> will be instructed to
			 compensate you for the favor you will confer on my mother and myself &mdash;
			 The 
			 <NAME TYPE="person"><ABBR EXPAN="General">Genl.</ABBR> Aunz</NAME>,
			 and all their family sent themselves to you, give my respects to 
			 <NAME TYPE="person">Mr Vanderlynn</NAME>. 
			 <ABBR EXPAN="Doctor">Doctr</ABBR> 
			 <NAME TYPE="person">Bell &amp; Smith</NAME>, and accept for yourself
			 assurances of the <UNCLEAR>esteem</UNCLEAR> and regard of your friend and
			 servant.</P> 
		  <CLOSER> 
			 <SIGNED> 
				<NAME TYPE="person">AJ Donalson</NAME></SIGNED> 
			 <ADDRESS> 
				<ADDRLINE>R.E.W. Earl</ADDRLINE> 
			 </ADDRESS></CLOSER> 
		</DIV1> 
